   <font class="MsgSubject">What happened to EveryPlayer?</font>
   <div align="right">
   <font class="ArticleTime">01/30/2004 10:48 PM CST</font>
   
   <div align="left">
   <font class="MsgText">The question is not whether we agree with Coray's opinions nor whether we believe the articles to be negative or cynical.  The question that we should be asking is whether or not the writing speaks to &quot;Everyman&quot;, every player.  In my opinion, and obviously several others, they do not.<p>The writer merely chose to reflect on the high end of the game and how any given change would affect him or his ability to play the same.  While he might not care for or think much of EQ or GoD or whatever is to come in the future, one would expect that he might elaborate on the coming changes for those who do, at the very least, from a player's perspective rather than dismiss them.<p>Sure you can go to Sony and read all about what is coming, but that is not quite the same as reading a report by a player who has invested time and effort into the game and cares about what happens not only to him or his guild but also to the player base as a whole.  That is what set Mobhunter articles apart from other EQ sites.  Whether the writer (Moorgard, Kohath or Csensier) liked or disliked whatever nerf, change, new expansion or something Sony did or didn't do, the articles spoke to all levels of players and didn't dismiss, disregard, or patronize.<p>Regardless of Coray's views on EverQuest, the articles regarding EQ should reflect, or at the very least, appeal to the &quot;Everyman&quot; of the player base, as the readership of Mobhunter clearly does.     <br></font>
  </td>
 </tr>
